# AWS Credentials File (EXAMPLE - DO NOT COMMIT REAL CREDENTIALS)
# This file shows the format for ~/.aws/credentials
#
# NEVER commit your actual ~/.aws/credentials file!
# Store credentials using:
# - 1Password CLI
# - AWS SSO (sso_session)
# - aws-vault
#
# This file is in .gitignore for security.

# Example format if you choose to use API keys:
#
# [dfinitiv-brian]
# aws_access_key_id = AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE
# aws_secret_access_key = wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY
#
# [dfinitiv-mojo-dev-power-user]
# aws_access_key_id = AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE
# aws_secret_access_key = wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY

# Recommended: Use AWS SSO instead (configured in ~/.aws/config)
# Benefits:
# - No API keys to manage
# - Automatic credential rotation
# - MFA integration
# - Audit logging via SSO provider
#
# To use SSO:
# 1. Configure profiles in ~/.aws/config with [sso-session] and [profile]
# 2. Login with: aws sso login --profile dfinitiv-brian
# 3. Credentials are automatically cached and refreshed
